result.execSummary:
This case has not been concluded. Unless a judgment of conviction is entered, the defendant is presumed innocent of all charges.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

of Conversion to Civil Commitment, signed and filed. 
Copy of  this order along with criminal complaint, competency report, given to the deputy sheriff.

Defendant Dayna R Cheeseman in court via Zoom with attorney Haley E Wentz.  Julie D Knyszek appeared for the State of Wisconsin.
Case in court for Competency Review Hearing. Parties in receipt of examiner's report.  Parties in receipt of examiner's report. Parties do not contest findings.  Court finds defendant is incompetent and not likely to gain competency within the statutory time frame. State moves to the court to administratively suspend and close the proceedings. Defense does not object.  
Upon Petition for Conversion filed by Corporation Counsel requests the Court to revert the case to a Chapter 51 civil commitment. Court adopts the findings in the report, suspends the criminal proceedings, orders the case converted to a Chapter 51 Commitment. Court ordered defendant REMANDED into the custody of the Milwaukee County Sheriff's and defendant to be transported to FORTHWITH to Milwaukee County Behavioral Health Division. 
Order of Conversion to Civil Commitment Proceedings signed, filed and distributed.
Case put back on Branch 30 calendar per request of Judge Franke. Status Conference scheduled for June 30th, 2022 at 1:30pm
Case spun to Judge Franke, Branch 25 due to judge unavailability.

Attorney Jason Findling appeared in court on behalf of Haley E Wentz, defendant Dayna R Cheeseman not in court, in custody.  Brandon Schwebler appeared for the State of Wisconsin.

Court ordered matter adjourned back to branch 30.
  Status conference scheduled for June 24, 2022 at 01:30 pm.
Forensic evaluation ordered.  INITIAL APPEARANCE NOT HELD.  Trial court to address INITIAL APPEARANCE.

Attorney Haley E Wentz in court, defendant Dayna R Cheeseman not in court, in custody.  Thomas Hasle appeared for the State of Wisconsin. Attorney appeared by video means.  Court is advised by the defense there is reason to believe the defendant is not competent to proceed.  Pursuant to Sec. 971.14 (2) Wisconsin Statutes, Court found probable cause and ordered defendant examined by the Forensic Unit.  Order for Examination, signed and filed.   Defendant is advised this case is assigned to Judge Ashley, Branch 19.   Court ordered defendant REMANDED into custody of Milwaukee County Sheriff's Department.  Commissioner tolls any applicable time limits.  Doctor's Report Return scheduled for June 21, 2022 at 08:30 am.
